[{"ty":"is","ibi":1,"s":"[public]\nExperiment with Attribution Reporting: Handbook\nPublished on March 31st, 2022\n\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cThis document is part of a collection of developer guides to Please ask.\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cWe strongly recommend you set up debug reports during your initial testing.\n\u0011Changelog\nApril 5th: corrected the noise values\nDemo\nTry the live demo\nTo quickly generate real reports and see them in your browser, try the demo.\nFollow the instructions on the demo page.\nCheck out the demo code / Build your own prototype\n➡️ Check out the source code for the demo.\nYou can also run it locally, or fork and customize it as needed.\nTips for local debugging\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cUse Chrome Canary for local experimentation, to get access to the latest API features.\n\u0011Use Chrome Canary and turn on the experimental flag\nSee details in Testing the Privacy Sandbox ads relevance and measurement APIs. \nVisualize reports stored in your browser\nTo visualize attribution data and reports stored locally in your browser, open chrome://attribution-internals/.\nThis page displays source events, as well as event-level and aggregatable reports.\n*\nReports displayed in chrome://attribution-internals\nUse DevTools\nDevTools functionality will be added in the future to help you troubleshoot your configuration. \nIf you have suggestions on this, please post your ideas on the developer mailing list.\nGotcha\nFor local development, use consistent origins (e.g. for destination and attributionsrc). Pick one of localhost or 127.0.0.1, and use it everywhere. localhost and 127.0.0.1 are aliases but they\u0027re different origins, so this will impact in unexpected ways how your browser matches clicks/views and conversions. \nReceive reports immediately at your endpoint\nWhen debugging locally, configure your browser to remove delays and send reports to your endpoint immediately after they\u0027re generated.\nTo have your browser send all the currently scheduled reports listed in chrome://attribution-internals/, check the checkbox at the top of any reports table and click Send Selected Pending Reports.\n*\nManually send the pending reports listed in chrome://attribution-internals to the specified endpoint\n\nTo have your browser always send reports immediately, enable the flag chrome://flags/#conversion-measurement-debug-mode and restart your browser.\nGenerating event-level reports\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cTake a look at the demo and demo code. The demo includes all the features listed in this section.\n\u0011Example event-level report\n\u0010\u0012\u001c{\n  \"attribution_destination\": \"https://shoes.example\",\n  \"randomized_trigger_rate\": 0.0000025,\n  \"report_id\": \"c0a71e17-1373-4971-9134-1ec6d5752342\",\n  \"source_event_id\": \"583443813872129\",\n  \"source_type\": \"event\",\n  \"trigger_data\": \"2\"\n}\n\u0011\n\u0010\u0012\u001cKey\n\u001cDescription  \n\u0012\u001cattribution_destination\n\u001cThe eTLD+1 where the attribution was triggered.\n\u0012\u001crandomized_trigger_rate\n\u001cThe browser\u0027s noise rate when the report was generated.\n\u0012\u001creport_id\n\u001cA unique ID for the report, automatically generated by the browser. It can be used for server-side deduplication in case of retries. See details.\n\u0012\u001csource_event_id\n\u001cThe source event ID.\n\u0012\u001csource_type\n\u001cThe type of source. Either navigation (click) or event (view).\n\u0012\u001ctrigger_data\n\u001cThe data associated with the attribution trigger, i.e. the conversion data.\n\u0011Detect the feature\nBefore you use the API, detect if it\u0027s available on the page. To do so, run the following code:\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cif (document.featurePolicy.allowsFeature(\u0027attribution-reporting\u0027)) {\n  // the Attribution Reporting API is enabled\n}\n\u0011\nIf this feature detection check returns true, the API is allowed in the context (page) where the check is run. \nHowever, this isn\u0027t a guarantee that the API is usable on that page: the user may have disabled the API via their browser settings, or they may have other settings that prevent the API from being used. Learn more in Debug reports.\n\u0011Set up an endpoint to collect attribution reports\n➡️Example code\nExample code\nReports\nThe browser sends reports via HTTP POST requests. \nEach request contains one report. \nA report is included in the request body as JSON.\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c{\n  \"attribution_destination\": \"https://shoes.example\",\n  \"randomized_trigger_rate\": 0.0000025,\n  \"report_id\": \"c0a71e17-1373-4971-9134-1ec6d5752342\",\n  \"source_event_id\": \"583443813872129\",\n  \"source_type\": \"event\",\n  \"trigger_data\": \"2\"\n}\n\u0011Endpoint \nSet up an endpoint to receive attribution reports the browser sends:\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c{REPORTING_ENDPOINT}/.well-known/attribution-reporting/report-event-attribution \n\u0011\nREPORTING_ENDPOINT is the server that responded to the initial browser request to register a source, with the Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source header.\nFor example, if https://adtech.example responded, reports will be sent to the following endpoint: \n\n\u0010\u0012\u001chttps://adtech.example/.well-known/attribution-reporting/report-event-attribution \n\u0011Deduplicate reports\n\u0010\u0012\u001cThis is different from Deduplicate conversions.\n\u0011\nWhen the browser retries sending reports due to network unavailability, it may send the same report multiple times.\nTo mitigate this: \nUpon receiving a report, check its report_ID.\nIgnore the report if you\u0027ve already received a report with that same report_ID.\n(Optional) Change the attribution logic\nUse case\nBy default, the attribution model with this API is last-touch, meaning that a conversion is attributed to the most recent matching source event. \nYou can tweak this behavior by using source-side priorities. \nHow to prioritize specific clicks or views\nAdd the priority key to your source registration header.\nSet a higher priority for sources you wish to prioritize. Larger values denote a higher priority—for example, a source event with a priority of 2 takes precedence over a source with a priority of 1.\nOnly the report that matches the source event with the highest priority will be sent.\n➡️Example code\nChange the attribution to select less recent sources:\n\u0010\u0012\u001cconst currentTimestamp \u003d Date.now();\nconst priority \u003d - currentTimestamp;\n\n res.set(\n  \u0027Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source\u0027,    \n  JSON.stringify({\n\t// … all usual fields for that header\n      priority: `${priority}`\n    })\n );\n\u0011\n(Optional) Prioritize specific conversions\nUse case\nAssume that a user clicks an ad and converts four times: she visits the advertiser site homepage, then visits a product page, signs up to the newsletter, and finally makes a purchase.\nBut due to the three-report limit for clicks, by default, all subsequent reports after the signup (third conversion) will be dropped, including the purchase report. \nInstead, you can configure the API such that you do receive reports for conversions that you consider more important—for example, the purchase report.\nHow to prioritize specific conversions\nAdd the priority key to your trigger registration header.\nSet a higher priority for conversions you wish to prioritize. \n\nWhen an attribution is triggered for a given source event, if the maximum number of attributions (three for clicks, one for views) has been reached for this source—meaning that three (or one) reports are already scheduled for this source—the browser will:\nCompare the priority of the new report with the priorities of existing scheduled reports for that same source.\nDelete the report with the lowest priority to schedule the new report instead (and if the new report is the one with the lowest priority, it will be ignored and you won\u0027t receive it).\nIf no priorities are set, the browser will fallback to its default behavior: any checkout completion page that includes the conversion pixel. By default, the page reload will trigger a second conversion and you\u0027ll get two reports. \nThis is not desirable, because the user really has only made one purchase. You can change this behavior to only see one conversion in that case, by deduplicating conversions.\nHow to deduplicate conversions\nAdd the key deduplication_key to your trigger registration header.\nFor a given source, the browser will deduplicate trigger registrations that contain the same deduplication_key.\n(Optional) Define custom rules (filters)\nUse case\nFilters are flexible. Here are just two ways they can be useful, but there are many more:\nOnly count conversions for a specific product category, and filter out conversions for other categories.\nChoose trigger data based on source event data: because the bit limit for the trigger data is different depending on the source type—ad click (0-7) or view (0 or 1)—it can be convenient to dynamically assign the value of the trigger data depending on the source type.\nHow to declare filters\nOn source registration, add a new field filter_data to the header Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source.\nOn trigger registration, add a header Attribution-Reporting-Filters, or define filters directly in Attribution-Reporting-Register-Event-Trigger.\n➡️Example code\nUse filters to only attribute conversions only when the user converts on a specific product category: set the filter on source and trigger\nChoose trigger data based on source event data  \n\n(Optional) Multiple reporters\n\nIn this example, reporter-1.example and reporter-2.example are two distinct entities looking to generate and receive attribution reports.\nAt source registration time\nreporter-1.example receives a request from the browser.\nreporter-1.example sends a response that contains the Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source header. It could be a regular response but, in this example, it\u0027s a redirect to reporter-2.example.\nThe browser receives this response. It reads Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source and hence stores a source event, using reporter-1.example as the reporting origin. Because this request is a redirect, the browser also makes a new request to reporter-2.example.\nreporter-2.example responds with a regular response that contains the Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source header. The destination value in this header must be identical to the destination value of the Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source header set by reporter-1.example. Otherwise, the source will not be registered.\nThe browser receives this response; it reads Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source and stores a source event, using reporter-2.example as the reporting origin.\n\nIf reporter-1 intends to rely completely on reporter-2 as a measurement service, and do not intend to do any measurement themselves, reporter-1.example can omit the Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source header at Step 2.\nAt trigger registration time\nRequests can be redirected in the same way as for source registration. \nSource events and trigger events that have been generated by the same origins will be matched—respectively, reporter-1.example and reporter-2.example.\nGenerating aggregatable reports\nAbout aggregatable reports\nTo generate aggregatable reports, you need to generate contributions as a user converts.  Contributions from many users are then aggregated to produce a summary report.\nGuidance will be published in the future to help you adopt strategies to define the keys you need in the aggregatable reports; for now, this section focuses on how to implement client-side code to generate aggregatable reports. \n\n*\nAggregatable report displayed in chrome://attribution-internals\n\n\nGenerating aggregatable reports\nAggregatable and event-level reports\n\u0010\u0012\u001cFor a given event source, it\u0027s possible to generate both an event-level and an aggregatable report. Regardless of the report type:\nThe source debug key must be set in Attribution-Reporting-Register-Aggregatable-Source.\nThe trigger debug key must be set in Attribution-Reporting-Trigger-Debug-Key.\nSteps\nKeep your cookie-based measurement implementation.\nSet up an endpoint to handle the debug reports. The browser sends debug reports to an endpoint that\u0027s similar to the regular report endpoint, but has a debug chunk in the path: \n\u0010\u0012\u001chttps://adtech.example/.well-known/attribution-reporting\n/debug/report-event-attribution \n\u0011https://adtech.example is the origin of attributionsrc.\nSet the following cookie on the origin of the reporting endpoint (https://adtech.example in our example), \n\u0010\u0012\u001cSet-Cookie: ar_debug\u003d1; SameSite\u003dNone; Secure; Path\u003d/; HttpOnly\n\u0011\nThe origin of your reporting endpoint should be the same as attributionsrc\u0027s origin hence the cookie will be set at source registration time.\nThe browser will check for the presence of this cookie at both source and trigger registration.\nUpon registering a source, set in the header Attribution-Reporting-Register-Source a source debugging key debug_key. It must be a 64-bit unsigned integer formatted as a base-10 string. Make this key a unique ID, and make it different from source_event_id, so that you can differentiate individual reports that have the same source event ID. Map this key to additional source-time information you think will be relevant for you to debug.\n\t\n\u0010\u0012\u001cAttribution-Reporting-Register-Source:\nJSON.stringify({\n source_event_id: \u0027267630968326743374\u0027,\n destination: \u0027https://shoes.example\u0027,\n expiry: \u0027604800000\u0027,\n debug_key: \u00279876787656787634576\u0027\n})\n\u0011\nUpon registering a trigger, set a debugging key by setting an additional header Attribution-Reporting-Trigger-Debug-Key. Its value must be a 64-bit unsigned integer. Make this key a unique ID and map it to additional trigger-time information you think is relevant for you to debug.\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cAttribution-Reporting-Trigger-Debug-Key: \n1252537303093874645\n\u0011\nWhen an attribution is triggered, the browser immediately sends a debug report via a POST request to .well-known/attribution-reporting/debug/report-event-attribution. A debug report is identical to a regular report, but additionally contains both debug keys:\n\u0010\u0012\u001c{\n \"attribution_destination\": \"https://shoes.example\",\n \"source_event_id\": \"267630968326743374\",\n \"trigger_data\": \"3\",\n \"source_type\": \"navigation\",\n \"source_debug_key\": \"9876787656787634576\",\n \"trigger_debug_key\": \"1252537303093874645\"\n}\n\u0011\nCheck for regular reports you receive. If a report has an identical \u003csource_debug_key, trigger_debug_key\u003e pair as one of the debug reports, match them. \n\nHow to use debug reports\nUse debug reports to pinpoint missing reports\nIf a conversion took place (according to your cookie-based measurement system) and a debug report was received for that conversion, this means the conversion was successfully registered.\n\nFor each debug attribution report, check if you\u0027re receiving a regular attribution report that matches the two debug keys.\n\nWhen there\u0027s no match, it can be for a number of reasons. Learn more.\nDebiase reports (\u003d Correct the noise)\nDebiasing event-level reports\nDespite the noise added to event-level reports as a protection mechanism, it\u0027s possible to recover the accurate number of conversions. \nSee how in the debiasing script. We\u0027ll add detailed guidance here on how to use this script in the near future.\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001cUser privacy isn\u0027t impacted by this debiasing technique, because you can\u0027t determine whether a specific event\u0027s conversion data was noised. This only gives you an accurate conversion count at an aggregated level.\n\u0011Resources\nAll developer guides for Attribution Reporting\nAppendix\nReport scheduling for aggregatable
